[[Image:Doyohbi Kyoto 1936.gif|thumb|200px|The tabloid ''Doyōbi'', founded by Masakazu Nakai]] {{nihongo|'''Masakazu Nakai'''|中井 正一|Nakai Masakazu, alternative romanization Nakai Shōichi<ref>Iwamoto, Kenji. "[http://ci.nii.ac.jp/Detail/detail.do?LOCALID=ART0008702382&lang=en Film Criticism and The Study of Cinema In Japan: A Historical Survey (PDF)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813151222/http://ci.nii.ac.jp/Detail/detail.do?LOCALID=ART0008702382&lang=en |date=2011-08-13 }}". ''Iconics'' vol. 1 (1987). Accessed 28 November 2009.</ref>}} (14 February 1900 - 18 May 1952) was a Japanese [[aesthetics|aesthetician]], [[film theorist]], [[librarian]], and [[social activist]].
==Career== Born in [[Hiroshima Prefecture]], Nakai studied philosophy at [[Kyoto University]], particularly [[aesthetics]] under [[Yasukazu Fukuda]].<ref name="kotobank">{{cite web|url=http://kotobank.jp/word/%E4%B8%AD%E4%BA%95%E6%AD%A3%E4%B8%80|title=Nakai Masakazu|work=Nihon jinmei daijiten + Plus|publisher=Kōdansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=12 January 2011}}</ref> He started the [[dōjinshi]] ''Bi hihyō'' in 1930, which changed its name to ''Sekai bunka'' in 1935.<ref name="kotobank" /> He became a lecturer at Kyoto University while being active in left-wing social movements, protesting Japan's tilt towards [[fascism]] and promoting popular forms of culture through such concepts at the "logic of the committee."<ref name="kotobank" /> He founded the popular culture tabloid ''[[Doyōbi]]'' (Saturday) in 1936, but was arrested for his activities in 1937 and lost his university position.<ref name="kotobank" /> After [[World War II]], he continued his political activism by teaching philosophy as part of the Hiroshima Culture Movement and by running for governor of [[Hiroshima Prefecture]], only losing by a narrow margin.<ref>Leslie Pincus, "A Salon for the Soul: Nakai Masakazu and the Hiroshima Culture Movement," ''positions'' 10.1 (2002), pp. 173-194.</ref> He was appointed the first Vice Librarian (''fukukanchō'') of the [[National Diet Library]] in 1948.<ref name="kotobank" />
==Selected bibliography== * {{cite book|last=Nakai|first=Masakazu|title=Nakai Masakazu zenshū|year=1981|publisher=Bijutsu Shuppansha|language=Japanese}} * {{cite journal|last=Nakai|first=Masakazu|title=Film Theory and the Crisis of Contemporary Aesthetics|journal=Review of Japanese Culture and Society|date=December 2010|volume=22|pages=80–87}}
